        <h1>How to Brush Your Teeth in Bellevue WA</h1>
        <img class="page-hero-img" src="http://www.dental.inceptionimages.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/child-brushing-teeth-smiling-pigtails.jpg" alt="Child Brushing Teeth Smiling" loading="eager" decoding="async" onerror="this.onerror=null;this.src=’http://www.dental.inceptionimages.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/child-brushing-teeth-smiling-pigtails.jpg’" />
        <p>Brushing teeth is something that all of us do every day. It’s been emphasized since childhood how important it is to perform this daily regimen. We were always told if we stick with it, we can enjoy healthy teeth that don’t require expensive dental procedures.</p>
        <p>But while we all acknowledge the importance of brushing teeth in Bellevue WA, many people still do not brush their teeth correctly. Here are the fundamentals you need to keep in mind to ensure that when you do brush your teeth, you’re giving yourself the maximum amount of protection.</p>
        <hr />
        <h2>Brushing Your Teeth in Bellevue WA</h2>
        <p>In a perfect world, you would brush your teeth every time you eat. Anytime you put something in your mouth and eat it; you are exposing your teeth to plaque. Plaque attaches itself to your teeth and works to decay the tooth enamel or infect the gums. More plaque coats your teeth with every meal or snack.</p>
        <p>While it’s not practical for many people to brush every time food is consumed, it’s important to maximize brushing opportunities. Twice a day is the minimum number of times you should brush. Once at the start of your day, after hours of sleeping and potential plaque build-up, and once at the end of your day after eating and snacking.</p>
        <hr />
        <h3>Brushing Technique</h3>
        <p>Contrary to what toothpaste commercials show, only a small, pea-sized bit of toothpaste is required. Here are the fundamentals of proper brushing technique:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>Use only a small, pea-sized bit of toothpaste</li>
          <li>Select fluoridated, ADA-approved toothpaste to protect enamel and help reverse early tooth decay</li>
          <li>Hold the brush at a 45-degree angle to your teeth and gums</li>
          <li>Use a gentle, circular motion to remove plaque — no harsh scrubbing required</li>
          <li>Brush all surfaces: chewing surfaces, front, back, tongue, and roof of mouth</li>
          <li>Avoid brushing gums too hard, as this can cause bleeding or injury</li>
          <li>Proper brushing takes only two minutes</li>
        </ul>
        <p>If you use a powered toothbrush, hold it at the proper angle and let the toothbrush do the work as you move it across all areas of your mouth. Once again, only two minutes are required.</p>
        <hr />
        <p>Brushing teeth doesn’t have to be either harsh or time-consuming. With the right technique, it can be a brief, efficient, but essential oral health experience that is easy to do twice a day. <a href="/contact-us/" class="text-link">Contact our team at AnaBella Family and Cosmetic Dentistry</a> in Bellevue WA today for more information.</p>
